---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Aetna International in France', level: 2 },
  { id: 'puma-transition', text: 'PUMA Transition Strategy', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-compliance', text: 'Visa Compliance', level: 2 },
  { id: 'france-network', text: 'Network Coverage in France', level: 2 },
  { id: 'plans-and-pricing', text: 'Plans and Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'us-coverage', text: 'US Coverage Advantage', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-its-for', text: 'Who Should Choose Aetna', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Health Insurance in France', href: '/countries/france/insurance' },
  { title: 'Aetna International Review', href: '/providers/aetna-international' },
  { title: 'Aetna vs GeoBlue', href: '/compare/aetna-international-vs-geoblue' },
];

const planColumns = [
  { key: 'plan', header: 'Plan' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage' },
  { key: 'francePrice', header: 'France (Age 50)' },
  { key: 'usIncluded', header: 'US Coverage' },
];

const planRows = [
  { plan: 'Pioneer', coverage: 'Inpatient + Emergency', francePrice: '€150-200/mo', usIncluded: 'Full integrated' },
  { plan: 'Pioneer Prime', coverage: 'Inpatient + Outpatient', francePrice: '€200-280/mo', usIncluded: 'Full integrated' },
  { plan: 'Pioneer Platinum', coverage: 'Comprehensive', francePrice: '€280-380/mo', usIncluded: 'Full integrated' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'factor', header: 'Factor' },
  { key: 'aetna', header: 'Aetna International' },
  { key: 'mutuelle', header: 'PUMA + Mutuelle' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { factor: 'Monthly Cost (Age 50)', aetna: '€200-280', mutuelle: '€30-150' },
  { factor: 'US Coverage', aetna: 'Full Aetna network', mutuelle: 'None' },
  { factor: 'Coverage Level', aetna: '100% worldwide', mutuelle: '~100% in France' },
  { factor: 'Pre-existing', aetna: 'Varies by plan', mutuelle: 'Full coverage' },
  { factor: 'Wait Time', aetna: 'Immediate', mutuelle: '6-9 months from arrival' },
  { factor: 'Portability', aetna: 'Worldwide', mutuelle: 'France only' },
  { factor: 'Best For', aetna: 'Pre-PUMA, US expats', mutuelle: 'Long-term residents' },
];

const hospitalColumns = [
  { key: 'city', header: 'City' },
  { key: 'hospitals', header: 'Private Hospitals' },
  { key: 'directBilling', header: 'Direct Billing' },
];

const hospitalRows = [
  { city: 'Paris', hospitals: 'American Hospital of Paris, Hôpital Américain, Clinique Turin', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Paris Region', hospitals: 'Clinique des Champs-Élysées, Hôpital Privé des Peupliers', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Lyon', hospitals: 'Clinique du Parc, Hôpital Privé Jean Mermoz', directBilling: 'Verify' },
  { city: 'Nice/Riviera', hospitals: 'Centre Hospitalier Princesse Grace (Monaco), Clinique Saint-George', directBilling: 'Verify' },
  { city: 'Bordeaux', hospitals: 'Clinique Saint-Martin, Polyclinique Bordeaux Nord', directBilling: 'Verify' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Aetna International Health Insurance in France"
  description="Guide to using Aetna International in France. US network for American expats, visa-compliant coverage, and PUMA transition strategy."
  headline="Aetna International Health Insurance in France"
  subheadline="Full US network access for American expats in France. Cover your visa requirements and stay protected while waiting for PUMA enrollment."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/france-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get an Aetna France Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/providers/aetna-international"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Aetna International in France</h2>
  <p>
    France ranks among the world's best healthcare systems, and for American expats, Aetna International bridges the gap between US and French care. During the 6-9 month wait for PUMA enrollment, Aetna provides visa-compliant coverage—and keeps your US healthcare access intact for visits home.
  </p>
  <p>
    France requires private insurance for visa applications. Aetna meets these requirements while offering something local French insurers can't: seamless US coverage when you return to see family or need a US specialist.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">1.7M+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Providers (US + intl)</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">€30K+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Exceeds visa minimum</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">24/7</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">English support</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Get a France-Specific Quote"
    description="See what Aetna International costs for US expats in France."
    buttonText="Get Quote"
    buttonHref="/providers/aetna-international"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="puma-transition">PUMA Transition Strategy</h2>
  <p>
    France's PUMA (Protection Universelle Maladie) provides excellent public healthcare, but you can't access it immediately. Here's how to plan your insurance timeline:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">The Timeline</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
      <li><strong>Months 1-3:</strong> Private insurance required (no PUMA eligibility yet)</li>
      <li><strong>Month 3:</strong> Apply for PUMA enrollment</li>
      <li><strong>Months 3-9:</strong> Continue Aetna while PUMA processes</li>
      <li><strong>Month 6-9:</strong> Receive Carte Vitale, switch to PUMA + mutuelle</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>Aetna's Role</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Covers you from day one—visa-compliant</li>
    <li>Provides full coverage during 6-9 month PUMA wait</li>
    <li>24/7 English support while navigating French bureaucracy</li>
    <li>US network access for trips home during this period</li>
    <li>Cancel when your Carte Vitale arrives (no long-term commitment)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>After PUMA Enrollment</h3>
  <p>
    Once enrolled in PUMA, most expats switch to the French system:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>PUMA (Sécurité Sociale):</strong> Covers ~70% of medical costs</li>
    <li><strong>Mutuelle:</strong> €30-150/month top-up for the remaining ~30%</li>
    <li><strong>Total:</strong> Significantly cheaper than international insurance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    However, some American expats keep Aetna alongside PUMA for US coverage when visiting family.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-compliance">Visa Compliance</h2>
  <p>
    France's VLS-TS Visiteur visa (the main non-working visa for expats) has specific insurance requirements:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">French Visa Insurance Requirements</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
      <li>Minimum €30,000 medical coverage</li>
      <li>Hospitalization and emergency care included</li>
      <li>Medical evacuation and repatriation coverage</li>
      <li>Valid for entire intended stay</li>
      <li>Visa letter from insurer confirming coverage</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>Does Aetna Meet These Requirements?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Aetna Pioneer plans provide comprehensive coverage well above France's €30,000 minimum, and Aetna can provide the documentation French consulates require for visa applications.
  </p>

  <h3>Visa Documentation</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna provides:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Certificate of coverage in English and French</li>
    <li>Confirmation of coverage amounts exceeding €30,000</li>
    <li>Policy validity dates matching your visa request</li>
    <li>Contact information for the consulate to verify</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="france-network">Network Coverage in France</h2>
  <p>
    France has excellent private healthcare, especially in Paris and major cities. Aetna has direct billing arrangements with key facilities.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={hospitalColumns} rows={hospitalRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>The American Hospital of Paris</h3>
  <p>
    The jewel of Aetna's France network is the American Hospital of Paris (Hôpital Américain de Paris) in Neuilly-sur-Seine. This JCI-accredited facility offers:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Fully bilingual English/French staff</li>
    <li>American-trained physicians</li>
    <li>US-style care in a French setting</li>
    <li>Direct billing with Aetna—no claims to file</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Outside Paris</h3>
  <p>
    In other French cities, you may need to pay upfront and submit claims for reimbursement. French healthcare costs are regulated and reasonable compared to the US:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>GP visit: €25-50</li>
    <li>Specialist: €50-150</li>
    <li>Hospital day: €300-800</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Reimbursement is straightforward through Aetna's online portal.
  </p>

  <h2 id="plans-and-pricing">Plans and Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    Aetna Pioneer plans include US coverage—no add-on needed.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <em>Prices include worldwide coverage with full US access. Age 50 shown.</em>
  </p>

  <h3>Plan Recommendations for France</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pioneer:</strong> Hospital-focused. Good for visa compliance with lower premiums. Use French healthcare for routine care.</li>
    <li><strong>Pioneer Prime:</strong> The practical choice. Includes outpatient coverage for full protection during the PUMA wait.</li>
    <li><strong>Pioneer Platinum:</strong> Comprehensive. Best if you have ongoing health needs or want maximum coverage.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Navigator Plans (Modular Option)</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna's Navigator plans let you customize coverage—choose core hospital coverage and add modules for outpatient, dental, and vision. Good for reducing costs during the temporary pre-PUMA period.
  </p>

  <h3>Deductible Strategy</h3>
  <p>
    Since you'll likely transition to PUMA within a year, consider:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Lower deductible if you have health concerns during transition</li>
    <li>Higher deductible to save on premiums for a temporary policy</li>
    <li>French healthcare is affordable—you can pay routine care out-of-pocket</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="us-coverage">US Coverage Advantage</h2>
  <p>
    The main reason to choose Aetna over French insurers or other international options:
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">US Network Benefits</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
        <li>Full Aetna US network access</li>
        <li>Direct billing at US hospitals</li>
        <li>Aetna's negotiated US rates</li>
        <li>No separate add-on cost</li>
        <li>Coverage continuity if you return</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Why It Matters</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Many US expats visit family annually</li>
        <li>US specialists accessible for second opinions</li>
        <li>Medicare doesn't work abroad</li>
        <li>Coverage gap if you move back</li>
        <li>Paris is 8 hours from NYC</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Medicare Doesn't Work in France</h3>
  <p>
    US Medicare provides no coverage abroad (except rare border exceptions). For American retirees in France, Aetna effectively replaces Medicare while keeping US coverage active for visits home.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Built-In US Coverage"
    description="No surprise bills when visiting family or needing US care."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/providers/aetna-international"
  />

  <h2 id="who-its-for">Who Should Choose Aetna</h2>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />
  </div>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Ideal For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
        <li>US citizens moving to France</li>
        <li>VLS-TS Visiteur visa applicants</li>
        <li>Pre-PUMA transition period (first 6-9 months)</li>
        <li>Expats who visit the US regularly</li>
        <li>Those who might return to the US</li>
        <li>Anyone wanting English-speaking support</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Consider Alternatives</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Non-US expats (AXA may be better value)</li>
        <li>Budget-focused (French mutuelles cheaper long-term)</li>
        <li>Already PUMA-enrolled (mutuelle more practical)</li>
        <li>Those who never visit the US</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>US Totalization Agreement Note</h3>
  <p>
    If you're sent to France by a US employer or are self-employed with US ties, you may be ineligible for PUMA for up to 5 years under the US-France totalization agreement. In this case, Aetna becomes your primary insurance for much longer.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Is Aetna accepted for French visa applications?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Aetna provides coverage exceeding the €30,000 minimum and can supply the documentation French consulates require. They're experienced with visa letter requests.
  </p>

  <h3>Should I keep Aetna after I get my Carte Vitale?</h3>
  <p>
    Most expats switch to PUMA + mutuelle, which is significantly cheaper (~€30-150/month total vs. €200-380/month for Aetna). However, if you visit the US regularly or want to maintain US coverage, you could keep Aetna as a supplement.
  </p>

  <h3>Does Aetna replace Medicare in France?</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna provides coverage abroad that Medicare doesn't offer. For US retirees in France, it serves as Medicare replacement during your pre-PUMA period and provides US coverage for visits home.
  </p>

  <h3>How does Aetna compare to French mutuelles?</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna costs more (€200-380/month vs. €30-150/month for mutuelle) but offers worldwide coverage and US network access. Mutuelles only supplement French public care. Different tools for different needs.
  </p>

  <h3>Can Aetna cover the 6-9 month PUMA wait?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. This is the primary use case. Start Aetna before your move, use it during the transition, then decide whether to keep it or switch to PUMA + mutuelle.
  </p>

  <h3>What about pre-existing conditions?</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna applies medical underwriting. Pre-existing conditions may be excluded or subject to waiting periods. PUMA has no pre-existing condition exclusions, which is one advantage of the French system once you're enrolled.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Coverage in France?"
    description="Get a personalized Aetna International quote for your France move."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/providers/aetna-international"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. French visa requirements, PUMA enrollment rules, and insurance policies change. We are not insurance brokers, immigration consultants, or tax advisors. Verify all information with the French consulate, CPAM, and Aetna International before making decisions.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
